\begin_layout Subsection
Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The work done by all forces in moving a system from an initial configuration
 1, to a final configuration 2 can be written to be (assuming that the masses
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the constituent particles of the system are constants)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
W_{12} & = & \sum_{i}\int_{1}^{2}\mathbf{F}_{i}.d\mathbf{s}_{i}\label{eq:work}\\
 & = & T_{2}-T_{1},\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the total kinetic energy of the system: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T & = & \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}m_{i}v_{i}^{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W_{12} & = & \sum_{i}\int_{1}^{2}\mathbf{F}_{i}.d\mathbf{s}_{i}\\
 & = & \sum_{i}\int_{1}^{2}\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\left(e\right)}.d\mathbf{s}_{i}+\sum_{ij,i\neq j}\int_{1}^{2}\mathbf{F}_{ji}.d\mathbf{s}_{i}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\left(e\right)}$
\end_inset

 stands for an external force and 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{ji}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is the internal force on the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th particle due to the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th particle and so we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}\left(\sum_{i}m_{i}\mathbf{s}_{i}\right) & = & \sum_{i}\mathbf{F}_{i}^{\left(e\right)}+\sum_{ij}\mathbf{F}_{ji},\\
 & = & \sum_{i}m_{i}\ddot{\mathbf{s}_{i}}=\sum_{i}m_{i}\dot{\mathbf{v}_{i}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{ij}\mathbf{F}_{ji}=\sum_{ij,i\neq j}\mathbf{F}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{ii}=0$
\end_inset

, as a particle does not exert a force on itself, and where we have assumed
 that the mass is a constant.
 Hence, using that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mathbf{s}_{i}/dt=\mathbf{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W_{12} & = & \sum_{i}\int_{1}^{2}m_{i}\dot{\mathbf{v}_{i}}.\left(\mathbf{v}_{i}dt\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{i}\int_{1}^{2}d\left(\frac{1}{2}m_{i}v_{i}^{2}\right)=T_{2}-T_{1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d\left(\frac{1}{2}m_{i}v_{i}^{2}\right)}{dt} & = & m_{i}\mathbf{v}_{i}.\dot{\mathbf{v}_{i}}\\
\implies d\left(\frac{1}{2}m_{i}v_{i}^{2}\right) & = & m_{i}\mathbf{v}_{i}.\mathbf{\dot{v}}_{i}dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

