\begin_layout Subsection
Conservative force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
conservative
\emph default
 force is such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\oint\mathbf{F}_{c}.d\mathbf{s} & = & 0,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

i.e.
 the work 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{12}$
\end_inset

 (see Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:work"

\end_inset

) is the same for any physically possible path between points 1 and 2.
 This condition is equivalent to stating that a conservative can be written
 in the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{F}_{c} & = & -\nabla V\left(\mathbf{r}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is usually called the 
\emph on
potential energy
\emph default
*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is a direct consequence of the Gradient Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:The Gradient Theorem"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Energy conservation theorem for conservative forces:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, for a conservative system, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{12}$
\end_inset

 can also be calculated to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W_{12} & = & V_{1}-V_{2},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{c}=-\nabla V\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, for some scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{F}_{c} & = & -\frac{dV}{d\mathbf{s}},\\
\mbox{i.e. }\left(\mathbf{F}_{c}\right)_{i} & = & -\partial_{s_{i}}V
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mathbf{s}$
\end_inset

 is a differential path length.
 Hence, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf{F}.d\mathbf{s} & = & -dV\\
\implies W_{12} & = & \int_{1}^{2}\mathbf{F}.d\mathbf{s}=-\left(V_{2}-V_{1}\right)\\
 & = & V_{1}-V_{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

which implies that energy is conserved for for a conservative system*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From the above equation, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{12}=V_{1}-V_{2}$
\end_inset

 and from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:work"

\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{12}=T_{2}-T_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Combing the two we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{1}-V_{2} & = & T_{2}-T_{1}\\
\implies V_{1}+T_{1} & = & T_{2}+V_{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

