 resulting from the external field.
 Expanding this additional term as a Taylor series in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we obtain that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U_{e}\left(x,t\right) & = & U_{e}\left(0,t\right)+x\left.\partial_{x}U_{e}\left(x,t\right)\right|_{x=0}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The first term can be omitted from the Lagrangian because it is a function
 of time only (see comment 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Lagrangian-unaffected-by-time"

\end_inset

).
 Denoting 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\partial_{x}U_{e}\left(x,t\right)\right|_{x=0}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $-F\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, which can be interpreted as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

external "force" acting on the system in the equilibrium position
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we obtain that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
L & = & \frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}kx^{2}+xF\left(t\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence, we obtain the following EOM: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\ddot{x}+\omega^{2}x & = & F\left(t\right)/m\label{eq:EOM forced oscillation}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The solution to the above equation is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x\left(t\right) & = & \frac{1}{\omega}Im\left[\xi\right]\\
\xi\left(t\right) & = & \dot{x}+i\omega x\\
 & = & \exp\left(i\omega t\right)\left(\int_{0}^{t}\frac{1}{m}F\left(t\right)\exp\left(-i\omega t\right)dt+\xi\left(t=0\right)\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
