\begin_layout Subsubsection
Energy transfer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The energy of a system executing forced oscillations is naturally not conserved,
 since the system gains energy from the source of the external field.
 Let us determine the total energy transmitted to the system ...
 assuming its initial energy to be zero.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The energy gained by the system at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 when we assume that the force is finally released is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta E=E\left(t\rightarrow\infty\right)-E\left(t=t_{0}\right) & = & E\left(t\rightarrow\infty\right)=\frac{1}{2}m\left|\xi\right|^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}m\left|\int_{t_{0}}^{\infty}\frac{1}{m}F\left(t\right)\exp\left(-i\omega t\right)dt+\xi\left(t=t_{0}\right)\right|^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\sum_{i}\dot{q}_{i}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{q}_{i}}-L$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:energy lagrangian"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}kx^{2}+xF\left(t\right).$
\end_inset

 so (not including terms induced from external forces, specifically 
\begin_inset Formula $xF$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & \dot{x}m\dot{x}-\frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}kx^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}kx^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega^{2}x^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

At time 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, the force is finally released so we have 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\infty\right)=\frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega^{2}x^{2}=\frac{1}{2}m\left|\xi\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E\left(\infty\right) & = & E\left(t=t_{0}\right)-\frac{1}{\omega}\im{\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dt\xi\left(t\right)\dot{F}\left(t\right)}\\
 & = & E\left(t=t_{0}\right)-\frac{1}{\omega}\im{\int dt\exp\left(i\omega t\right)\left(\int_{0}^{t}\frac{1}{m}F\left(t\right)\exp\left(-i\omega t\right)dt+\xi\left(t=t_{0}\right)\right)\dot{F}dt}\\
 & = & -\frac{1}{\omega}\im{\int dt\exp\left(i\omega t\right)\left(\int_{0}^{t}\frac{1}{m}F\left(s\right)\exp\left(-i\omega s\right)ds\right)\dot{F}\left(t\right)dt}\\
 & = & -\frac{1}{\omega}\im{\frac{1}{m}\int dt\int_{0}^{t}ds\exp\left(i\omega\left(t-s\right)\right)F\left(s\right)\dot{F}\left(t\right)dt}\\
 & =\\
\\
 & = & -\frac{1}{\omega}\im{\frac{1}{m}\int dt\int_{0}^{t}ds\exp\left(-i\omega s\right)F\left(s\right)\dot{F}\left(t\right)dt}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Taking that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}=-\infty$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\left(t=t_{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 *
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E\left(t=t_{0}\right) & = & \frac{1}{2}m\dot{x}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}m\omega^{2}x^{2}-xF\\
 & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(-\infty\right)=0$
\end_inset

 (this is the beginning of time, before the force was applied; the force
 has been applied at a discrete point in time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{f}$
\end_inset

 and by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<t_{f}$
\end_inset

) and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
